value.0: A transparent golden gemstone formed in ancient times by solidified tree sap. It is reputed to ward off disease. Followers of the drow goddess Lolth believe that finding spiders encased in amber is a sign of her favor.

A translucent semi-precious stone found in small sizes, also known as andalusite. Flashes greenish-red or brownish-red if faceted correctly.

In Faern, andar is the name for andalusite, a semi-precious stone usually found in streambeds as tumbled pebbles or crystals

Angelar's skin, also seen as aasimon's skin and angel's skin, was not a mineral but a coral found on reefs in shallow tropical waters.

This gem got its name from the sorcerer Angelar, who (according to legend) became a wereshark with complete control over his transformations. The story tells that he consumed this coral in powdered form mixed into sea water and then cast polymorph self to become a shark.

A magnificent transparent pale blue-green gemstone

Aquamarine is a precious stone found mainly in northern Faern, is used as adornment by many barbarian tribes of the region

An opaque mottled deep blue stone worth around 10 gp. It is sacred to the dwarven deity Gorm Gulthyn

Some families of Calishite, Halruaan, Myth Drannan, and Netherese descent had the tradition of strapping lucky azurite stones to their bodies while cooking or working at a forge. They often mounted them on armbands and slid them up all the way to the armpits to keep them concealed, protected, or just out of the way.[

A translucent striped gemstone. It may be brown, blue, white or red. Worth around 10 gp. Agate is reputed to provide safe and resful sleep.

Banded agate is an ornamental stone used in furniture inlays, inexpensive brooches, and carried as a "soothe stone" to be fondled or rubbed between the fingers in order to prevent nervous fidgeting by merchants during tense negotiations.

A smooth, spherical and extremely hard opaque sea-green gem found in huge fist-sized chunks,  Unique to the Forgotten Realms, and noted for its property to periodically emit light.

Beljurils, also known as fireflashils or fireflashes, are gemstones unique to the Realms and highly prized for their unusual properties.These jewels are found in ancient rock formations, usually in blue claystone.

A translucent dark green gemstone, with black mottling and golden flecks.  

Calling a rogue (or anyone who operated in the shadows, away from the spotlight) "black as a black opal" was an ironic way of saying that they had a good heart without causing them too much embarrassment.

Back opals were considered a prized gem among the drow. It was actually one of their favorites.

The drow deity Vhaeraun showed his pleasure or displeasure by making his followers stumble on or change the quality of a black opal in their possession

Pearls were considered sacred by followers of Deep Sashelas and Dugmaren Brightmantle--appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found. Specifically, white pearls were sacred to followers of Savras, and black pearls were sacred to followers of Shargaas and Vhaeraun

DESCRIPTION:
if wet the shine of this stone will "bleed" away and leave a dull surface untill dryed again. it normally of a dark muddy green color with flakes in red and orange
LORE:
claimed to prevent high bloodpresure or rapid bleeding from cuts it also known for helping in decision making or where one need to clense the body from illness. some also say it can dry a body of blood if put into a beating heart
The corundum family of gemstones consists of ruby and sapphire. Corundum is very compact, dense, and lacks gemstone cleavage. It's also the second hardest natural mineral after diamond.

A transparent pale blue gemstone worth around 10 gp.

Large blue quartz crystals are the preferred ingredient to produce a gem of seeing, especially in ancient times. More modern uses include being a material component in casting scrying spells and, when properly sliced, prepared, and enchanted, as lenses for the various magical eyes, such as eyes of charming, eyes of the eagle, and eyes of minute seeing.

Blue Topaz is a brilliant blue colored, semi-precious gemstone It is worn to gain financial stability, fame, self-confidence and good health.

Topaz stones are considered sacred by followers of Deneir, Horus-Re, and Gaerdal Ironhand appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found. The blue variety of topaz was sacred to followers of Eldath.

A translucent pale blue gem, with green and golden mottling. It is sacred to the dwarven deity Gorm Gulthyn.

They are the favored gems to use in helms of brilliance.Their affinity for igniting, releasing, and controlling fire made them useful in formulating inks to inscribe scrolls, enchanting immersions for making items, and mounting on devices as a focal point of discharge.

Best known for their whimsical shapes and wide variety of sizes and colors, the character of a freshwater pearl is found in its distinctive surface texture and the warmth of its luster. 

Pearls are used as a material component in many spells, particularly those that reduced acids to plain water, and neutralize poison. Crushed to a powder, pearls are used in creating all types of magic mirrors. Well-known magical items included the pearl of power, the pearl of the sirines and the pearl of wisdom.

Golden yellow topaz is typically known as imperial topaz and golden topaz. ... Moreover, the golden yellow topaz is a powerful stone for the manifestation of personal desires and intentions, via the will. 

Topaz are often used to create items that conferred protection from magical effects because this stone protected the item itself from trauma due to force, acid, fire, petrification, and disintegration. It is the preferred component when making a gem of brightness because topaz takes on the hardness of mithral when so enchanted.

An opaque gray-black gemstone worth around 10 gp.It is reputed to aid warriors and heal wounds.It is sacred to the drow deity Vhaeraun.

Hematite is an ornamental stone that was favored by fighters.

Milky or white quartz caused by trapped water or gas bubbles, worth around 10 gp. Occasionally contains grains of gold.

Hyaline is sensitive to magic and will give off a blue glow whenever magic is activated, triggered, cast, or passed within 20 feet of a hyaline gem.

An opaque white opal which becomes transparent and iridescent in water. Worth around 50 gp

Hydrophane is a variety of opal that is highly prized by sailors and the aquatic races of Faern because its true beauty is only visible when wet

Iol, also known as violet stone, was the name by which iolite (cordierite) was commonly known in the Realms. Such stones were sacred to Deneir, the Scribe of Oghma.

Iol stones were the best component for use in making ioun stones

A gemstone worth around 50 gp. Often gray or bluish-violet. In the Forgotten Realms it is called "iol" or "violet stone". It changes its color depending on the direction of sunlight. Also called cordierite in some worlds.
Ivory, also known as dentine, was the primary substance that makes up the teeth or tusks of all mammals and some other creatures. It was carved for artistic ornaments and also many practical uses

This rare jewel had a fiery orange hue and was as hard and durable as sapphire and ruby. Each stone has a heart of fire that flickers like a candle bright enough to be seen in the dark but not enough to illuminate even nearby objects.This property made it highly prized for adornment on cloaks and gowns worn by the well-to-do.

Jacinth are considered a prized gem among the drow and is favored in particular by their wizards.

A translucent green or white gem.

Bards and other musicians in the Realms wore jade for luck as it was said to improve musical talent. The stones were also favored by the gods Baravar Cloakshadow, Erevan Ilesere, and Urogalan.

In Kara-Tur, jade was believed to block the passage of all manner of ghosts.

An opaque gemstone in colors of blue, black or brown. It is reputed to make the bearer immune to poison. Black jasper is sacred to the drow deity Vhaeraun.

Jasper was a common stone among the drow, a gem worn by drow of average station. It was under common use as an inlay-stone or decoration.

Jet was a deep black gemstone that is hard enough to take facets and was often used in simple pendants or as part of a larger setting. In the wealthy commercial centers of Amn, Calimshan, and Sembia, jet is worn to represent sorrow and mourning.This custom is also practiced in Waterdeep and Westgate.

A rare, transparent and extremely had gemstone native to the world of Faern, where they are also known as "frozen tears". Legend has it that they are the crystallized tears of necromancer-kings, and visions of the past can be seen in them. They are is sacred to the dwarven deity Dugmaren Brightmantle.
Laeral's tears is the Realms name for beryllonite, named after the famous sorceress Laeral Silverhand. They are signs of favor from the god Finder Wyvernspur and signs of disfavor from the god Hoar.
Lapis lazuli, incorrectly called lazurite in the South, is an ornamental stone found in the Realms an opaque blue stone with yellow flecks. It is reputed to grant courage

A translucent white gemstone with a pale blue glow.  A folk belief claims that moonstone causes lycanthropy. Followers of the drow goddess Eilistraee believe that finding moonstone is a sign of her favor.

A translucent pink or yellowish-white stone, with mossy gray or green markings. 

Moss agate enhances serenity and increased stability so it is used in powdered form in sleeping draughts and in all manner of potions to assist the mixing of components that might otherwise clash. Its powers are such that it can be safely added to any potion and even failed attempts does not explode or turn poisonous.

A soft white, cream, fawn or brownish-pink iridescent gemstone related to moonstone, native to the Forgotten Realms. It is also known as albite or pigeon stone

Nelvine is used as a component in spells that disguise a person or object without changing the target's true nature. It is also powdered for the magical ink to inscribe such spells on scrolls.

Obsidian, also known as natural glass or volcanic glass, comes in different grades and varieties, some more prized than others. Low grade obsidian, called pitchstone, is not as shiny or smooth as gem quality obsidian but is useful for grinding and abrading.  A variety called blacksmoke obsidian is primarily found in Tashalar, sold in the local bazaars.A rare form of obsidian, called rainbow obsidian, is considered a semi-precious stone.

Volcanic in origin, obsidian is a hard, black, glassy stone with a natural sheen. Common obsidian can be chipped into arrowheads, cutting blades, or even weapons if large enough. As an ornamental stone, it is usually tumbled, polished into smooth cabochons, or carved into figurines and fingerbowls. It was often worn as jewelry or inlaid on bracers or pectorals of copper or bronze. Package handlers in Waterdeep wear obsidian rings with a cutting edge on the inside for snipping twine.

An opaque black or white gemstone, or with bands of black and white. Onyx is used as a component of the spell animate dead. A folk belief claims that it causes discord between enemies. Black onyx is sacred to the drow deity Vhaeraun.

Orl crystals are only found in very soft rock inside "blue caves" such as those near Wheloon, and are believed to be exclusive to the northern half of Faern.

Orls are considered sacred by followers of Bahgtru appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found. The red hue of orl is sacred to followers of Haela Brightaxe

Orprase was another name for pollucite, a gemstone especially favored by followers of Tymora.

These gems are eagerly sought by followers of Tymora and those that know their secret. One orprase stone, powdered and mixed into at least 3 oz (90 ml) of wine that had been consecrated to Tymora by a full-fledged priest of that faith, is said to grant extraordinary good luck.

An opaque lustrous white sphere formed by aquatic creatures. Sometimes yellow or pink, sometimes gold or silver. 

Pearls are considered sacred by followers of Deep Sashelas and Dugmaren Brightmantle--appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found. Specifically, white pearls are sacred to followers of Savras, and black pearls are sacred to followers of Shargaas and Vhaeraun.
A valuablue transparent deep bright green gemstone, This the clearest bright green emeralds can fetch a hefty price. The emerald dragon is named for this gemstone.

A transparent rich olive green gemstone, it is reputed to ward off enchantments

Peridots are considered sacred by followers of Gaerdal Ironhand and Yondalla--appropriate for sacrifice, or to concecrate for use, or recognize as boons or omens when found.
A gemstone found in fiery yellow or rich purple.  This one is purple and should fetch a pretty price.

Ravenar, also called schorl, was a variety of tourmaline mainly in demand in the North, and less so in other lands.

Ravenar occurred in long crystals like other varieties of tourmaline and was a solid gloss black. Ravenar was commonly used for inlay work on weapons and accouterments.

Ravenar, like all tourmalines, could absorb any spell cast upon it and immediately convert it into three lightning bolts that blasted outward in straight lines from the crystal facets in directions chosen by the caster. This act consumed the gem in the process

Ravenars were considered prized gems among the drow. Their lesser deity Vhaeraun was known to occasionally send ravenars to show his favour or disfavour to his followers.

A transparent gem in colors of red, brown-green, or violet. This is the red variety.

Garnets come in many colors but, as of the Year of Wild Magic, 1372 DR, the violet hue was the most valuable and called rhodolite[ while the other varieties and fallen out of favor and were valued in the fancy stone price range.

In some faiths and folklore, garnets are considered the solidified blood of the divine avatars.[4] To the uninitiated, garnets has the reputation of being worthless for magical use.

Garnet is a common stone among the drow, a gem worn by drow of average station. There was a distinction regarding color preference depending on the profession of the wearer. Deep red is favored by warriors, while the priestesses of Lolth favored violet ones.

Red Tears, also known as Tempus' weeping, or Tempus's weeping are gemstones found only in the Realms in deep mines or anywhere old stone had been exposed by erosion, mining, or rockfall.

The church of Tempus believes that their deity appeared during the Time of Troubles in both Battledale and the Fields of the Dead, but which occurred first has not been established. What is known is the Foehammer journeyed across four famous battlefields, using or creating a circular chain of one-way portals, and leaving a trail of red tears behind him to mark the path he took. If they were real gems, they have long since been collected or stolen. What remained behind were actually illusions of Tempus's weepings, only visible to those who successfully met the challenges at each stop along the trail.

This feature soft, rosy hues. The banded patterns it displays are similar to those you would find in malachite.

Rodochrosite stones are considered sacred by followers of Lliira appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found.

transparent variety of quartz that is valued for its clarity and total lack of colour or flaws

This clear semi-precious stone is considered lower grade if it is soft or brittle, but is frequently used to adorn furniture or decorative head gear. High grade samples free from impurities are used for optics, eyeglasses, magnifying glasses, and prisms.

The translucent variety of quartz

Rose Quartz is the stone of universal love.  It restores trust and harmony in relationships, encouraging unconditional love.  Rose Quartz purifies and opens the heart at all levels to promote love, self-love, friendship, deep inner healing and feelings of peace.  Calming and reassuring, it helps to comfort in times of grief.
Sanidine is an ornamental stone found on the surface of sand dunes and gravel screes. Sanidine is favored by the nomadic, desert-dwelling Bedine and facet-cut to ring-stone size or smaller.

This gemstone was used in the crafting of luckstones and in the creation of devices that offered protection from evil or from bodily harm. Carrying or wearing a carnelian generally improved the owner's luck by a small amount. A properly prepared and enchanted carnelian could be sacrificed in dire need to gain a second chance at some failed feat of strength, ability, or survival. The person had to immediately touch the special stone, which then disappeared in a flash of bright light, and try again.

An opaque red-and-white banded gemstone.

Sardonyx is characterized by alternating stripes of carnelian (also known as sard) and white onyx. These semi-precious stones are usually cut cabochon to show off the banded pattern but are also used in cameo work.

Smoky Quartz, also known as cairngorm, or moorland topaz, was a variety of quartz that was often found in massive deposits. The black variety of this stone was called morion and is used in necromancy.

Smoky quartz was a common stone among the drow, a gem worn by drow of average station, albeit they used only blue ones.

Smoky quartz is sacred to the dark Chultan demigod Eshowdow

Spodumene came in two distinct color families each with their own name. Stones in the pink to purple range were known as kunzite while the emerald-green variety was called hiddenite. Both types were hard, easily cleaved, durable, and produced beautiful large faceted gems. The color of the kunzite variety unfortunately faded with time and because of this was called "ghost stone". 

If this stone was sprinkled with holy water (at least three drops) it had the ability to open wizard locked doors and items on contact. The gemstone was not consumed by this, but the holy water was used up the spodumene had to be anointed for each attempt.

When cut cabochon, star rose quartz reflected or transmitted light in a star-like pattern. It was used as a centerpiece in modest jewelry, like pectorals and earrings, worn mainly by the matrons of long-established houses.

While carrying or wearing one of these stones, the star rose quartz had a chance to deflect a spell directed at the bearer. Because of this property, this semi-precious stone was an alternate spell component for all abjuration spells and any divine magic of the protection sphere that could use a material component that wasn't specially prepared for a particular spell.

Star Sapphire was a very rare form of sapphire that exhibited asterism

Asterism is a reflective optical effect that highlights a white six-pointed star on the surface of cabochon-cut stones. Star sapphires were more opaque than regular gem-quality sapphires. About one in a thousand sapphires was a star sapphire

Star sappires were often used in making and decorating devices and objects to ward off hostile magic, such as globes of invulnerability, allowing them to be effective against stronger spells.Many spells could be enhanced by adding a star sapphire to the material component. For example, the duration of an antimagic shell could be extended for more than two hours beyond the usual time limit

Star sapphires were considered prized gems among the drow. They considered it somewhat of a lucky charm for those who could use magic and a very bold choice for others. It was particularly used by old priestesses.

Tchazar was the Realms name for aragonite which occurred in long, prism-shaped crystals that were straw-yellow and very fragile

This gemstone was important to those who feared magical scrying because tchazar interfered with scrying devices and spells, rendering anything within 2 ft (60 cm) of a tchazar stone blurry and indistinguishable. The effect was the same regardless of how the tchazar was cut (cabochon, facted, or natural crystal) so it was used to adorn many personal items and locations where privacy was of utmost importance. This magical smoke screen effect was lost if the tchazar stone was shattered.

This agate was a golden hue with dark brown stripes that exhibited a silky luster called chatoyancy. This ornamental stone was named for its color and its stripes.

Legends about this mineral said that it repelled undead and restless spirits, but had never been proven to be true.Regardless of this lack of evidence, the legend generated demand for tiger eye to be powdered and used in inks to mark caskets, sarcophagi, and tombs to prevent the dead from rising.

Tomb jade was rare and commands a high price in the Realms.Normal jade is considered a fancy stone, but after being mined and possibly worked, then buried for great lengths of time, it changed color and was worth ten times as much. 

Powdered tomb jade is an ingredient in potions of undead control. It can also be used as a talisman for turning undead, granting a priest a second chance to turn an undead creature after a failed attempt.

Tourmaline can be found in a wide variety of colors, the more common being pale shades of blue, brown, gold, green, pink, red, and silver pearl. White or colorless tourmaline was called waterstar. If multiple colors occurred in the same crystal, it was known as rainbow tourmaline and was priced in the higher precious stone range.Black tourmaline is called ravenar and is considered a gem stone. 

Tourmalines are considered sacred by followers of Deneir appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found. The rainbow variety of tourmaline is sacred to followers of Mystra.

This ornamental stone was an opaque blue to greenish-blue, and usually occurred with blotches of darker hues in the mix.

Turquoise stones are considered sacred by followers of Aerdrie Faenya and Erevan Ilesere appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found.

Elves value the pure color stones (without the darker mottling) for casting sky-related magic and mages use turquoise in the creation of items related to flight. It is also used as a good luck charm by horsemen who would put a small shard of turquoise in their horse's harness to ward off misstep or trail hazards. Turquoise has a slight gleam when it comes near gold and was therefore associated with prosperity. Foredawn was the best time of day to apply an immersion containing turquoise.

Garnets came in many colors but, as of the Year of Wild Magic, 1372 DR, the violet hue was the most valuable and called rhodolite while the other varieties and fallen out of favor and were valued in the fancy stone price range.In later years, even the violet hued stones dropped in value.

If mounted on a weapon and properly enchanted, garnets could double or triple the damage dealing potential of that weapon. The most propitious time of day to begin these weapon enchantments was high morn

Garnet is a common stone among the drow, a gem worn by drow of average station. There is a distinction regarding color preference depending on the profession of the wearer. Deep red is favored by warriors, while the priestesses of Lolth favor violet ones.

Violine gems are purple and volcanic in nature.

Violine stones are considered sacred by followers of Ghaunadaur appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found. 

This gem is proof against mummy rot. A creature with mummy rot only had to touch a violine crystal and the mummy rot was removed. The violine is completely consumed by this process. If this stone comes into contact with an actual mummy, it burst and damaged the mummy. If a mummy is destroyed by contact with violine, the resulting mummy dust was inert and could not be used as a spell component or for other magical purposes.

Water opal is a clear to translucent gemstone with small flashes of color. Opals without any color were considered plain hyalite, an inferior stone, and were nearly worthless. Water opal is rare and highly prized for use in decorating mirrors and windows and in the creation of scrying devices such as crystal balls.
Waterstar are a colorless and transparent gemstone. Gem-quality stones have to be flawless and can yield large faceted jewels that sparkled.

The substrate of opal is usually an opaque pale blue, while the inclusions flashed green to gold.Opals are usually cut cabochon or used as inlays.

Opals were considered sacred by followers of Lliira appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found. White opals specifically were sacred to followers of Hathor

Pearls is formed of layers of tchazar (aragonite) around a bit of grit or other irritant, growing inside a mollusk over the span of a few years. This slow process give pearls a smooth surface with a deep, rich luster.

Pearls are considered sacred by followers of Deep Sashelas and Dugmaren Brightmantle--appropriate for sacrifice, or to be consecrated for use, or recognized as boons or omens when found. Specifically, white pearls are sacred to followers of Savras, and black pearls are sacred to followers of Shargaas and Vhaeraun.

Zircon is volcanic in origin, found in igneous rock formations. It was a brownish crystal that turned pale blue when heated sufficiently and can be cut into faceted gemstones. Zircons are sometimes substituted for more valuable gems to fool the uninitiated, but anyone with a passing knowledge of gemology (a jeweler, a dwarf, or even a seasoned adventurer) could notice the difference. Zircons have an affinity for magic and can be enchanted easily, making them a favorite for use in creating magical items.  

Ircon is a common stone among the drow, a gem worn by drow of average station. It is considered the "fine stone" among them.
